## ğŸ“ Key Points

- Variables = boxes that store data
- Every variable has a TYPE (int, string, etc.)
- Must DECLARE before using
- Use meaningful names (age, not x)
- C# is case-sensitive!

---

## ğŸ’¡ New Concepts

### Concept 1: Variable Declaration

**What it is:**
Telling C# "I need a box to store data"

**Syntax:**
```csharp
int age;  // Declare
age = 16; // Assign value
```

**Or combined:**
```csharp
int age = 16;
```

**Why it matters:**
Can't use variable without declaring it first!

---

### Concept 2: Data Types

**int** â†’ Whole numbers
```csharp
int age = 16;
int score = 100;
```

**string** â†’ Text
```csharp
string name = "Sylvester";
string city = "Hamburg";
```

**double** â†’ Decimal numbers
```csharp
double price = 19.99;
double temperature = 36.5;
```

**bool** â†’ True/False
```csharp
bool isStudent = true;
bool isRaining = false;
```

---

### Concept 3: Naming Rules

**Good names:**
âœ… age (clear!)
âœ… userName (describes what it holds)
âœ… totalPrice (meaningful)

**Bad names:**
âŒ x (what is x??)
âŒ temp (too vague)
âŒ asdfgh (meaningless!)

**Rules:**
- Start with letter or underscore
- Can't use spaces (use camelCase)
- Can't be C# keywords (int, string, etc.)

---

## ğŸ’» Code I Wrote

### Example 1: Basic Variables
```csharp
using System;

class Program {
    static void Main() {
        // My first variables!
        string name = "Sylvester";
        int age = 16;
        string city = "Hamburg";
        bool isLearning = true;
        
        Console.WriteLine("Name: " + name);
        Console.WriteLine("Age: " + age);
        Console.WriteLine("City: " + city);
        Console.WriteLine("Learning C#: " + isLearning);
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Name: Sylvester
Age: 16
City: Hamburg
Learning C#: True
```

**What I learned:**
- Can mix different data types
- + operator combines strings
- bool prints as True/False

---

### Example 2: Age Calculator (MY OWN PROJECT!)
```csharp
using System;

class Program {
    static void Main() {
        Console.WriteLine("=== Age Calculator ===");
        
        Console.Write("Enter your birth year: ");
        string input = Console.ReadLine();
        int birthYear = int.Parse(input);
        
        int currentYear = 2025;
        int age = currentYear - birthYear;
        
        Console.WriteLine("You are " + age + " years old!");
        
        if (age >= 18) {
            Console.WriteLine("You're an adult!");
        } else {
            Console.WriteLine("You're a minor!");
        }
    }
}
```

**What's special:**
- Used int.Parse() to convert string to int (NEW!)
- Did math with variables (2025 - birthYear)
- Added if/else for bonus feature
- **I figured this out myself!** ğŸ‰

